      <li xml:id="exer_sec51-3">
        <p>
          Use mathematical induction to prove each of the following:
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="exer_inductionsum-a">
              <p>
                For each natural number <m>n</m>,
                <m>2 + 5 + 8 + \cdots + \left( {3n - 1} \right) = \dfrac{{n\left( {3n + 1} \right)}}{2}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For each natural number <m>n</m>,
                <m>1 + 5 + 9 + \cdots + \left(4n - 3 \right) = n \left(2n - 1 \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="exer_51-3c">
              <p>
                For each natural number <m>n</m>,
                <m>1^3 + 2^3 + 3^3 + \cdots + n^3 = \left[ {\dfrac{{n\left( {n + 1} \right)}}{2}} \right]^2</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Based on the results in <xref ref="prog_indexample"></xref>
          and Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_51-3c"/>, if <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>,
          is there any conclusion that can be made about the relationship between the sum
          <m>\left( {1^3 + 2^3 + 3^3 + \cdots + n^3 } \right)</m> and the sum <m>\left( {1 + 2 + 3 + \cdots + n} \right)</m>?
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_previnduction">
        <p>
          Instead of using induction,
          we can sometimes use previously proven results about a summation to obtain results about a different summation.
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="exer_previnduction-a">
              <p>
                Use the result in <xref ref="prog_indexample"></xref>
                to prove the following proposition: For each natural number <m>n</m>,
                <m>3 + 6 + 9 + \cdots + 3n = \dfrac{{3n\left( {n + 1} \right)}}{2}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="exer_previnduction-b">
              <p>
                Subtract <m>n</m> from each side of the equation in Part<nbsp/>(a).
                On the left side of this equation,
                explain why this can be done by subtracting <m>1</m> from each term in the summation.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Algebraically simplify the right side of the equation in Part<nbsp/>(b) to obtain a formula for the sum <m>2 + 5 + 8 + \cdots + \left( 3n - 1 \right)</m>.
                Compare this to Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_inductionsum-a"/>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec51-5">
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="exer_515a">
            <p>
              Calculate <m>1 + 3 + 5 + \cdots + \left( {2n - 1} \right)</m> for several natural numbers <m>n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="exer_515b">
            <p>
              Based on your work in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_515a"/>, if <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>,
              make a conjecture about the value of the sum <m>1 + 3 + 5 + \cdots + \left( {2n - 1} \right) = \sum\limits_{j = 1}^n {\left( {2j - 1} \right)}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use mathematical induction to prove your conjecture in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_515b"/>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_mod3conjecture">
        <p>
          In <xref ref="S_directproof"></xref>,
          we defined congruence modulo <m>n</m> for a natural number <m>n</m>,
          and in <xref ref="S_divalgo"></xref>,
          we used the Division Algorithm to prove that each integer is congruent,
          modulo <m>n</m>,
          to precisely one of the integers <m>0,1,2, \ldots ,n - 1</m>
          (<xref ref="C_congtorem">Corollary</xref>).
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the value of <m>r</m> so that
                <m>4 \equiv r \pmod 3</m> and <m>r \in \left\{ {0,1,2} \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the value of <m>r</m> so that
                <m>4^2 \equiv r \pmod 3</m> and <m>r \in \left\{ {0,1,2} \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the value of <m>r</m> so that
                <m>4^3 \equiv r \pmod 3</m> and <m>r \in \left\{ {0,1,2} \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For two other values of <m>n</m>,
                find the value of <m>r</m> so that
                <m>4^n \equiv r \pmod 3</m> and <m>r \in \left\{ {0,1,2} \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>,
                make a conjecture concerning the value of <m>r</m> where
                <m>4^n \equiv r \pmod 3</m> and <m>r \in \left\{ {0,1,2} \right\}</m>.
                This conjecture should be written as a self-contained proposition including an appropriate quantifier.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use mathematical induction to prove your conjecture.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec51-6">
        <p>
          Use mathematical induction to prove each of the following:
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="exer_516a">
              <p>
                For each natural number <m>n</m>, 3 divides <m>\left( {4^n - 1} \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For each natural number <m>n</m>, 6 divides <m>\left( {n^3 - n} \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          In Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_mod3conjecture"/>,
          we proved that for each natural number <m>n</m>,
          <m>4^n \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>.
          Explain how this result is related to the proposition in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_516a"/>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
